task.summary: Default task
Some cleanup of Room.java (needs more on naming of hitmesh methods)
You are now given a personalized message from your killer upon your death.
Spike suicides upon hopeless situations (like moved out of world with dock)
Add a mountain trail setting, where you can fall off the edge.
Made mtns and player hurt mechanism slightly less annoying
New inventory is half-built. I don't see how we'll get as many items in here, though.
FWIW, Trolls and stuff on the mountain trail chase you.
Roughly double FPS. Profiling told me that Window.build() was taking 150ms; now takes 40-70ms.
repackaging - make folder for Zone 1, etc

Back from vacation. Tried making a new Menu object so we could get a clean starrt at building a new inventory screen.
Having some trouble, though.
Make red-text-when-Player-Hurt better, and generally quiet sout. I did stuff.

The humble beginnings of a truly user-friendly menu. Push Q to experience the New Menu Beta™
The A button is used to confirm options, rather than ENTER.

I'm on vacation, but there is also internet here too! Testing GitHub on my laptop.
I also added a new window in the Spells equipment page. It now shows what you have currently equipped. Even though you can already figure it out beforehand....

THE INTRO IS COMPLETE!
feel free to watch it. It's good. I rate 2 out of 2 stars.

THE INTRO IS COMPLETE!
feel free to watch it. It's good. I rate 2 out of 2 stars.
Because GitHub is weird.

I made the inventory properly display a list of items, spells, or equipment.
I'm almost there to a completely functional inventory! I also filled the inventory with junk for testing reasons.
The QUIT GAME feature now asks if you want to quit before doing so. It was kind of rude before then.

Equipping spells is now proper. The new menu merges even further into our current systems.
It will soon replace all of the old stuff. At some point the old stuff needs to cleaned up. Eventually.

Almost done re-making tutorial basement. Now slower paced and better at teaching the player.
Also improved Room's updateObjs so it doesn't stop updating objects halfway through upon reaching an error. Now we can have lots of objects on the screen and safely rely on that they will all properly update.
Also cleaned up output. That was a mess. Now useful stuff is dumped onto the output.
Improved updateObjs again. Now ConcurrentModification errors and NullPointerExceptions are mostly eradicated.

Added a Heal spell. Spells that aren't damaging ARE possible.
Use the Heal spell as an example for adding new non-offensive spells.

New Tutorial Complete. Yeah.
I already know that you are just going to try out the newest version. So what's the point? But I know I must commit and push..... Every day, every hour.....

The waiting period after casting spells now depends on how much mana was spent.
The more you spend, the longer you wait. Now there are two stats for consider when choosing spells: Damage / Mana Consumed Efficiency, and Mana Consumption They ARE different. Heavy-hitting spells take longer to recover than lighter-weight ones.
The player must choose between high damage or high fire rate.
Min time: .25 seconds Max time: 2 seconds.

Added a new display mode for spells: Orientation-reliant.
Using the new feature, I have remade the visuals of Astral Dart. It now looks more pathetic.
PROGRESS.

You should honestly read the descriptions to some of these updates.
For actual content I just re-wrote some of the tutorial messages. Nothing much.

Something confusing is happening. ImageOrg removeAllButPlayer....
...Is not operating on all layers. some are left over when the room changes. Look at the output to see what's going on.
Posting this as a backup before making some major reworkings of ImageOrg. Ctrl + Z may not be sufficient.

ImageOrg removeAllButPlayer fixed.
Because elements of layers slide to the left when an element is removed, removeAllButPlayer skipped processing an element every time one was removed.
It now forms a list of what to remove and then does so AFTER processing all the layers. It works like a charm.
Fix a hole in the wall (in the art of the Source hole)

Apparently all the rooms were broken when you (Riley) changed the method names of numerous Room methods.
You can say thank you.
Some behind-the-scenes cleanup of the inventory menu.
Some behind-the-scenes cleanup of the Item and Player class.
Some behind-the-scenes cleanup of the inventory and Item menus.
Redo name changes and comments in Room.java

Improve menu summoning from Player
Made it so the lagacy menus don't ever come up, and fixed a buggy thing I made a couple commits earlier which made both the legacy and new menus appear when 'w' was pressed.

Fixed objects not unpausing after dismissing menu.
Heh, heh. Sorry.

Spikes now exist!
They hadn't had a timer starting, which is why they didn't appear.
I also fixed Room.java:flusheObjList() recursing indefinately, which happened once (or rather, 1019 times)

More cleanup, more bugfixes.
Specifically: > You can press ENTER as well as A to select things in menus > Calling Player.reportPos() repeatedly in a Room should be discouraged, as it can be triggered by pressing the single quote > Updated Javadoc of ThePit.java so it didn't falsely boast of capabilities and purpose > Consolidate Room.cleanLayersForExit(), objs.clear(), and stopping the timers on all items with the single, long-winded method removeAllObjectsAndLayersButPlayer(). This should now be standard to call at the end of a level.

Fix menu selector jumping by twos!
Specifically, being able to open inventory when player was frozen (the order of methods in Player.update(). I think that two instances of the inventory came up somehow. Maybe. Anyway.
I also cleaned up some of the misleading / depreciated methods in Player.java, like setPrimarySpell(), and adjusted whitespaces, and ran a 'format code' which altered about a hundred lines.

Tweaks to Spike.java. Unfortunately, it may increase the player's health.
Bye!
Make Mountains.java usable with the new string return system for levels.

Made the FlavorText system actually functional.
Then I added our first side character: Dennis

Made a huge display optimization; Dropped items don't work....
Before: ~5ms to update once stable After: ~0.5ms to update once stable
Instead of parsing through all the characters of each layer, ImageOrg/Window now have a top-down perspective on the stack of layers. It now for loops the width x height of the screen, and on each "pixel" it goes down the list of layers until it finds an opaque space or a character.
It basically skips characters that don't need to be processed.
Unfortunately, dropped items don't display yet.... :(
However, hurrah for optimized code!

I think the droppedItem no display bug has..fixed itself?
My computer might be sentient. I need you to run the game and see if dropped items show up.
I'm giving up on partial rendering. Also the player isn't a ghost anymore.
Beginning work on monster pathfinding.
Pathfinding's major bug fixed. Huzzah!
Pathfinding is completed. \( ' v ' )/
